{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491011","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491011"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:27:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:27:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"803"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"803","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/803"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.1,0.23,0.58,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"803"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86566"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"803","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/803"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"803"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70848"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"3505"},{"type":"tags","id":"5601"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"832"},{"type":"contributions","id":"921"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1175"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28392"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86566","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/86566"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old woman is being reviewed in the pre-admission assessment clinic for a left total knee replacement. Apart from diet-controlled type 2 diabetes and some mild hypertension, she has no significant medical or surgical history. She is on amlodipine as her only regular medication. She will require some pre-operative investigations.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Echocardiogram","Oral glucose tolerance test","Coagulation screen","Twelve-lead ECG","Chest X-ray"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe pre-operative assessment should include a judicious choice of investigations. The Australian and New Zealand College of Anaesthetists (ANZCA), the American Society of Anesthesiologists (ASA), and the Association of Anaesthetists of Great Britain and Ireland recommend against routine investigations for all patients pre-operatively, instead opting for investigations based on clinical indications. This recommendation is based on the evidence of little benefit and high false positive results associated with routine testing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile investigations are not routinely indicated, selective testing is appropriate in specific circumstances such as patients with known disease or risk factors that may impact the surgical outcome. Some examples include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EComplete blood examination (indicated in patients over 65 undergoing major surgery or younger if there is expected large blood loss; or in a history of anaemia)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERenal function (indicated with use of nephrotoxic agents)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EElectrolytes (indicated if history of electrolyte abnormality or medication associated with electrolyte derangement)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECoagulation (indicated if history suggests personal or familial bleeding disorder)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood glucose (indicated in known or suspected diabetics)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EECG (indicated in known cardiovascular disease or high risk patients)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChest X-ray (may be indicated in cardiopulmonary disease)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this patient\u0027s case, given her history of type 2 diabetes and hypertension, she is at increased risk of an adverse cardiac event, and therefore a \u003Cstrong\u003Epre-operative ECG\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEchocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E is not routinely indicated unless there is a suspicion of significant cardiac dysfunction or valvular heart disease, which is not suggested by the patient\u0027s history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eoral glucose tolerance test\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary as the patient already has a diagnosis of diabetes, and her blood glucose levels can be monitored through simpler means.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecoagulation screen\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated unless there is a history of bleeding disorders or anticoagulant use, neither of which is present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Echest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E is not routinely required unless there is a history of significant cardiopulmonary disease, which is not indicated in this patient\u0027s history.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A pre-operative ECG is an essential investigation in an older patient with diabetic or cardiovascular co-morbidities.","Pre-operative investigations should be tailored to the patient\u0027s medical history and risk factors rather than performed routinely."],"references":["Committee on Standards and Practice Parameters; Apfelbaum JL, Connis RT, Nickinovich DG; American Society of Anesthesiologists Task Force on Preanesthesia Evaluation; Pasternak LR, Arens JF, Caplan RA, Connis RT, Fleisher LA, Flowerdew R, Gold BS, Mayhew JF, Nickinovich DG, Rice LJ, Roizen MF, Twersky RS. Practice advisory for preanesthesia evaluation: an updated report by the American Society of Anesthesiologists Task Force on Preanesthesia Evaluation. Anesthesiology. 2012 Mar;116(3):522-38. doi: 10.1097/ALN.0b013e31823c1067. PMID: 22273990. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22273990/","O\u0027Neill F, Carter E, Pink N, Smith I. Routine preoperative tests for elective surgery: summary of updated NICE guidance. BMJ. 2016 Jul 14;354:i3292. doi: 10.1136/bmj.i3292. PMID: 27418436. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27418436/","Rusk MH. Avoiding Unnecessary Preoperative Testing. Med Clin North Am. 2016 Sep;100(5):1003-8. doi: 10.1016/j.mcna.2016.04.011. PMID: 27542420. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27542420/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70848"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"803"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70848","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/70848"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-22T14:36:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-22T14:37:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"803"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86566"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type